f an already hidden workforce. She also explores the historical roots of farmworkers' predicaments and examines the ethnic shift from Black to Latino workers. With an analysis that can be applied to local food concerns around the country, this book challenges the reader to consider how the mentality of the alternative food movements implies a comprehensive food ethic that addresses workers' concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAgricultural laborersxAbuse ofxHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aAgricultural laborersxAbuse ofzHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aAgricultural laborersxEmploymentxHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aAgricultural laborersxEmploymentzHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aLabor policyxHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.)xUnited StatesxHudson River Valley. 0aLabor policyzHudson River Valley (N.Y. and N.J.). 7aTechnology & Engineering / Agriculture / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957060423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520957060.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles